article.headline: Heat avoid season's first three-game skid
article.linkText: With Wade sidelined, Heat ride Shaq to victory
article.story:
OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Even blurry-eyed and headache-laden, Shaquille O'Neal is too much for anybody to handle. Playing with a red right eye a night after being poked, O'Neal had 26 points and 12 rebounds as the Miami Heat avoided their first three-game losing streak of the season with a 98-91 win over the Golden State Warriors on Wednesday night. "I had a headache every time I looked to the right," O'Neal said. "This was a game we needed. We lost two in a row and didn't want to make it three in a row." Udonis Haslem added a career-high 22 points and 10 rebounds for the Eastern Conference-leading Heat, who played without top scorer Dwyane Wade because of back spasms and a rib contusion. Haslem shot 11-for-16. "When you've got to double-team Shaq or give help on Shaq, he's the guy you're most likely to leave," Golden State's Troy Murphy said. "If he starts hitting shots like that, you're out of luck." Miami bounced back from just its second two-game skid of the season by pulling away in the third quarter behind the aggressive play of Haslem, who notched his eighth double-double of the season. Miami shot 55.9 percent, and everyone who saw action scored. "I have to take pressure off the main guys," Haslem said. "With Dwyane out, more of the focus was on the big fellow." Murphy had 22 points and matched his season high with 17 rebounds for the cold-shooting Warriors, who have lost their last seven games -- all without leading scorer Jason Richardson, out with a sprained left ankle. Derek Fisher, starting in place of Richardson, had 17 points, six rebounds and three assists, but he had a hard time seeing Shaq, his former Lakers teammate. "I tried not to look at him," Fisher said. "It was strange." The Warriors' frustration came out when Cliff Robinson, defending O'Neal most of the night, picked up two technicals and was ejected with 5:50 remaining. He had to be held back from official Tony Brothers by several teammates and screamed the whole time as he made his exit from the court. Warriors owner Chris Cohan scurried out moments later. "He outweighs me by 100 pounds and I can't touch him?" Robinson said. "I let myself get frustrated by that." The Heat had struggled during their tough five-game road swing out West. O'Neal believes his team's troubles have been in part because the Western Conference is shooting better than the East, just not Golden State. Next up for Shaq: Another stop at Staples Center, this time to face the Los Angeles Clippers. It won't be a big deal for the big man, who already returned to L.A. to face the Lakers on Christmas Day. "It doesn't matter to me, because people know I built that arena and they will always know that," he said. "Everybody else now is just playing there. ... I'm through with trying to outdo other people. In my 13 years, I've killed everyone. There might be some new ninjas coming up, but I am Shogun, loved by no one." Before the game, Miami coach Stan Van Gundy said he'd "like to see a more consistent focus and intensity," especially on defense and the boards. His players obliged. "Our defense was the best its been in a long, long time," Van Gundy said. The Warriors struggled to hit open shots and were tentative in the paint against O'Neal. Mike Dunleavy started 1-for-10 before being pulled early in the third period as the Heat began the quarter with a 16-6 spurt to build a 64-53 lead. Dunleavy didn't return, playing only 20 minutes and scoring two points. Wade's absence made for more disappointment for Warriors fans who bought ticket packages to see certain top players. Already this season, Denver's Carmelo Anthony and Orlando's Grant Hill have missed games in Oakland. Shandon Anderson replaced Wade in the starting lineup, his first start since April 14 last year against Cleveland. He had eight points, seven rebounds and three assists. During its losing streak, Golden State has been outscored 676-610 and gone over 100 points only once. The Warriors fell to 11-25, four fewer wins than the team had a year ago through 36 games under fired coach Eric Musselman. The Warriors missed six straight shots to start the game, but got their first eight points from Fisher to keep things close. Miami shot 58.8 percent in the first half and held a 48-47 edge at the break.

Game notes
O'Neal shot 8-for-20 from the free-throw line. ... The Warriors' last win was a 111-105 home victory against Toronto on Dec. 29. ... Shaq said he knew Golden State had interest in acquiring him before he left the Lakers. "It's not that I didn't want to be here," he said. "They didn't move fast enough. I wanted to be traded that day." ... The Warriors drew a season-high 18,596 fans.
